  "prompt": "In a group of 50 people, what are the odds of 2 having the same birthday?",
  "response": "Let's calculate the probability that *no two* people in the group of 50 share a birthday. Then we can subtract that probability from 1 to find the probability that *at least two* people share a birthday.\n\nAssume there are 365 days in a year (ignoring leap years for simplicity).\n\n*   **Person 1:** Can have any birthday (365/365)\n*   **Person 2:** Must have a different birthday than person 1 (364/365)\n*   **Person 3:** Must have a different birthday than person 1 and person 2 (363/365)\n*   ...\n*   **Person 50:** Must have a different birthday than the previous 49 people (365-49)/365 = (316/365)\n\nSo, the probability that no two people share a birthday is:\n\n(365/365) * (364/365) * (363/365) * ... * (316/365)\n\nThis can also be written as:\n\n365! / ( (365-50)! * 365^50) = 365! / (315! * 365^50)\n\nCalculating this directly can be cumbersome.  A more convenient form is:\n\n\u220f (from i=0 to 49) of (365-i)/365\n\nCalculating this:\n\nProbability (no shared birthday) \u2248 0.0296\n\nTherefore, the probability that at least two people *do* share a birthday is:\n\n1 - 0.0296 = 0.9704\n\nSo, the probability that at least two people in a group of 50 share a birthday is approximately 97.04%.  In other words, the odds are very high that two people will share a birthday.\n\n**Answer:** The odds are approximately 97% that at least two people in a group of 50 share a birthday.\n",
